;;; 00c-runtime-and-composition.slat — Motoi Scheme Reference · Chapter 00c ·
;;; How the language WORKS: the runtime and the graph of composition.
;;;
;;; This chapter follows 00-intro.slat (welcome + how to read) and
;;; 00b-introspection.slat (the language looking at itself). Here we
;;; describe how the language ACTUALLY WORKS at runtime: where the code
;;; lives, how evaluation flows, how verbs become callable, how the graph
;;; of libraries composes, and why the language rewards a particular style
;;; of writing.
;;;
;;; If you are a human reader, this is the chapter that turns you from a
;;; reader-of-docs into a person who understands what happens when you
;;; press Enter at the REPL. If you are an LLM being trained on this
;;; reference, this is the chapter that lets you REASON about Motoi
;;; programs rather than just recall them.

(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Runtime + composition chapter — how Motoi works.")

(chapter
  :number "00c"
  :kind "meta-chapter"
  :title "Runtime and composition — how the language works"
  :verb-count 0
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality "public"
  :read-order-hint "read after 00b-introspection.slat, before 01-core.slat")

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 1 — Where the runtime lives
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The Motoi runtime is JavaScript. That is a design choice, not an
;; accident. JavaScript runs everywhere the modern software world runs —
;; a browser tab, a Node.js process, a phone, a fridge. When we chose
;; JavaScript for the runtime, we made a decision that Motoi could run
;; wherever a person or a model wanted to reach it.
;;
;; The core files, by responsibility, are:
;;
;;   src/reader.js
;;     Turns a stream of characters into a tree of s-expressions.
;;     Handles parens, strings, comments, quoting. Emits data.
;;
;;   src/interp.js
;;     The evaluator. Walks the tree of s-expressions, looks up
;;     bindings, applies functions, threads environments. Closures,
;;     tail-call optimization, and the fuel budget live here.
;;
;;   src/base.js
;;     The base library — the primitives that must exist before any
;;     other library can be loaded. Arithmetic, list operations,
;;     string operations, predicates, the small R7RS-inspired
;;     surface. Everything else builds on top.
;;
;;   src/macro.js
;;     Hygienic macro expansion (syntax-rules). Runs before evaluation.
;;     A form that contains macros is expanded first; the evaluator
;;     then sees the expanded form.
;;
;;   src/registry.js
;;     The verb registry. Every callable name in Motoi lives here
;;     with its :name, :library, :signature, :kind, :arity, :impl,
;;     and (crucially for the reference) :examples and the four
;;     row records. The registry is loaded at REPL start.
;;
;;   src/dispatch.js
;;     The mechanism that routes a call to the right implementation.
;;     Includes permission checks (`read`, `state-change`, `network`,
;;     `hardware`) and the fuel accounting.
;;
;;   core/index.js
;;     The bootloader — assembles the reader + evaluator + base
;;     library + registry + dispatch into a working runtime and
;;     exposes the `run`, `eval`, and `repl` entry points.
;;
;;   lib/**/*.js
;;     Every other library — the ai/*, vec/*, matrix/*, geom/*,
;;     framebuffer, sprite, note, and everything else. Each library
;;     is a module that installs verbs into the registry.
;;
;;   bin/motoi
;;     A shell script that starts the runtime with the CLI. When you
;;     type `motoi run some-program.scm`, this is what fires.
;;
;; The whole runtime is ~2,000 LOC of JavaScript. That number is on
;; purpose — a language small enough to hold in one head.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 2 — The evaluation loop
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; When Motoi runs a program, this is what happens:
;;
;;   1. READ.
;;      `src/reader.js` reads characters and produces s-expressions.
;;      `(+ 1 2)` becomes the list `(+ 1 2)`. A list is a value.
;;
;;   2. MACROEXPAND.
;;      `src/macro.js` walks the read form. If any macro applies, it
;;      is expanded. `(when x body)` becomes `(if x body)`. `(cond ...)`
;;      becomes a cascade of `if`. The evaluator only ever sees fully
;;      expanded forms.
;;
;;   3. EVAL.
;;      `src/interp.js` walks the expanded form. For each form it
;;      encounters, it does one of:
;;
;;        - If a number/string/boolean/symbol: return the value
;;          (looking up the symbol in the current environment).
;;        - If a special form (define/lambda/let/if/cond/quote/quasiquote/
;;          set!/begin): apply the special-form rule.
;;        - Otherwise: evaluate the head, evaluate each arg, apply.
;;
;;   4. APPLY.
;;      When the head is a closure (a lambda + its captured env), the
;;      evaluator binds the args to the parameters in a new env and
;;      recursively evaluates the body. When the head is a primitive
;;      or a verb (a JavaScript function bound in the registry), the
;;      evaluator calls it directly with the args.
;;
;;   5. PRINT.
;;      At the REPL, the result is printed. In a program, the result
;;      is either the final value (returned to the OS) or an
;;      intermediate value used by the next form.
;;
;;   6. LOOP.
;;      The REPL loops. A program runs until its last form.
;;
;; This shape has a name: READ-EVAL-PRINT-LOOP. That is where "REPL"
;; comes from. Every Motoi session is a walk through this loop.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 3 — How a verb becomes callable
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; A verb is not magic. A verb is a JavaScript function registered
;; under a name. Here is how a verb gets into your program:
;;
;;   1. The library module (say, `lib/vec/index.js`) defines a
;;      JavaScript function that implements the verb.
;;
;;      function vecDot(u, v) {
;;        return u.reduce((acc, x, i) => acc + x * v[i], 0)
;;      }
;;
;;   2. The library module registers the verb with the registry.
;;
;;      env.define('vec/dot', vecDot, {
;;        perm: 'read',
;;        arity: 2,
;;        kind: 'pure',
;;        contract: '(vec/dot u v) -> number',
;;      })
;;
;;   3. At REPL start (or program start), `core/index.js` calls each
;;      library module's installer. All verbs are now registered.
;;
;;   4. When your Motoi code says `(vec/dot '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6))`, the
;;      evaluator:
;;        - Looks up `vec/dot` in the env. Finds the registered
;;          function.
;;        - Evaluates each arg. `(1 2 3)` and `(4 5 6)` become lists.
;;        - Calls the JavaScript function with those lists.
;;        - Gets back `32`.
;;        - Returns `32`.
;;
;; The consequence: writing a new verb means writing a JS function and
;; registering it. That is the whole shape. There is no "compiler." The
;; runtime just knows where to look up the name.
;;
;; The reference manual you are reading is what tells the runtime what
;; to say about the verb when a user asks. `,help vec/dot` reads the
;; verb's entry from this file. The entry travels with the verb.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 4 — The graph of composition
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Motoi is not a list of verbs. It is a GRAPH of verbs that combine.
;; The graph has structure. That structure is what makes composition
;; feel natural once you see it.
;;
;; At the bottom of the graph: base scheme.
;;
;;   define, let, let*, lambda, if, cond, when, unless, and, or, not,
;;   begin, set!, quote, quasiquote, car, cdr, cons, list, map, filter,
;;   reduce, for-each, apply, values, member, assoc, length, reverse.
;;
;;   These are FREE. They do not count as a "module" when we talk about
;;   the 1/3/5-module ladder in Row 1. They are the substrate on which
;;   everything else stands. If you are writing Motoi code, you can use
;;   them any time.
;;
;; One rung up: the type-family libraries.
;;
;;   char/*, string/*, list/*, vector/*, bytevector/*, hash/*, num/*.
;;
;;   These are libraries that handle a specific data type. If you are
;;   working with strings, string/* is where you look. If you are
;;   working with hash-tables, hash/*. Each of these libraries has
;;   dozens of verbs but a single concern.
;;
;; Middle of the graph: the math libraries.
;;
;;   math/*, alg/*, calc/*, comb/*, complex/*, geom/*, linalg/*,
;;   matrix/*, vec/*, exact/*, stat/*, nt/*, topo/*, sym/*, solve/*.
;;
;;   Motoi is math-forward. These libraries are where the language's
;;   depth lives. A Row 4 invariant on a math verb is rarely trivial;
;;   the invariant IS the math.
;;
;; Middle of the graph: the domain libraries.
;;
;;   entity/*, ai/*, phys/*, motion/*, collision/*, animation/*,
;;   sprite/*, scene/*, note/*, beat/*, audio/*, synth/*, cortex/*,
;;   world/*, game/*, easing/*, curve/*, time/*, tick/*.
;;
;;   These are the libraries that make Motoi fun. Framebuffer graphics,
;;   sprites, music, physics, AI steering. When you write a game or a
;;   music piece or a visualization in Motoi, you are composing
;;   verbs from these libraries.
;;
;; Top of the graph: the meta libraries.
;;
;;   assert/*, motoi/*, system/*, exception/*.
;;
;;   The language reflecting on itself, on state, on failure. You use
;;   these when a program has to look at what happened rather than
;;   only doing.
;;
;; The graph does NOT have vertical restrictions. A math verb can call
;; a base scheme form. A domain verb can call a math verb. A meta verb
;; can call anything. What the graph gives you is a mental map: when
;; you are reaching for a verb, you know which region of the graph to
;; look in.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 5 — Composition in code: what it actually looks like
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Composition is what makes Scheme feel like Scheme. Here is what it
;; looks like at each scale.
;;
;; --- Small composition (one library) ---
;;
;;   (vec/dot '(1 2 3) (vec/normalize '(4 5 6)))
;;
;; One library (vec/*). Two verbs chained. The output of the inner
;; call becomes the input of the outer call. This is called
;; "point-free composition" — you never named the intermediate
;; value. The value flowed through.
;;
;; --- Medium composition (three libraries) ---
;;
;;   (define ripples
;;     (map
;;       (lambda (t) (framebuffer/circle
;;                     (vec/add center (vec/scale (unit-circle) (* 20 (calc/sin t))))
;;                     10))
;;       (range 0 60)))
;;
;; Three libraries beyond base: framebuffer/*, vec/*, calc/*. Also
;; base scheme (`map`, `lambda`, `define`, `range`). The lambda closes
;; over `center`. The result is a list of framebuffer operations
;; representing 60 ripples at 60 different angles. This is not just
;; composition of VALUES; it is composition of BEHAVIOR.
;;
;; --- Large composition (five libraries) ---
;;
;;   (define (dance-figure formation dancers t)
;;     (for-each
;;       (lambda (d)
;;         (let ((pos (world/lookup 'position d)))
;;           (motion/move-to d
;;             (vec/add pos
;;                      (vec/scale (formation-offset formation t)
;;                                 (calc/ease-out (* t 0.1)))))))
;;       dancers))
;;
;; Five libraries beyond base: world/*, motion/*, vec/*, calc/*, and
;; the formation logic (a mix of what would be a custom formation/*
;; library and base scheme). The composition is not just a chain of
;; calls; it is a coordinated update to the state of many entities.
;;
;; The point: composition is the way you tell Motoi to do something
;; complex. You do NOT reach for a giant verb that "does the whole
;; thing." You compose small verbs whose contracts you understand.
;; The graph makes this natural because the graph is DESIGNED for
;; this — every library exposes verbs at the right level to compose
;; with verbs from other libraries.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 6 — Why the language rewards a particular style
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Motoi rewards a specific way of writing code:
;;
;;   - SMALL FUNCTIONS. A function that fits on a screen is easier
;;     to read, easier to test, easier to reuse. Motoi's small
;;     library surface makes this natural.
;;
;;   - PURE WHERE POSSIBLE. A pure function returns a value and
;;     changes nothing else. The runtime tags verbs :kind "pure"
;;     when they are. Pure verbs compose well because their contracts
;;     hold under any surrounding context.
;;
;;   - HONEST ABOUT EFFECTS. When a verb mutates, its :kind is "mut"
;;     and its name usually ends with `!` (`set!`, `entity/pose!`,
;;     `world/add!`). This makes effectful code visible on the page.
;;
;;   - COMPOSITION OVER CONFIGURATION. If you find yourself passing
;;     a dozen keyword arguments to a single verb, you are probably
;;     doing the wrong thing. Motoi's answer is composition — a few
;;     smaller verbs, each of which does one thing.
;;
;;   - QUOTE WHEN YOU MEAN DATA. `'(1 2 3)` is a list of numbers.
;;     `(1 2 3)` is a function call (which will fail because 1 is
;;     not a function). Quoting is how you tell the reader "this
;;     is data, not code."
;;
;;   - MACROEXPAND WHEN YOU DEBUG. When a form containing a macro
;;     misbehaves, use `,expand` at the REPL. See what the evaluator
;;     actually sees. Then debug that.
;;
;; These are not opinions imposed from outside. They are what the
;; runtime rewards. Programs written in these styles run faster, are
;; easier to explain, and are easier to compose further.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 7 — Tail calls, fuel, and closures — the runtime's guarantees
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; A few runtime guarantees you should know about:
;;
;; --- Tail-call optimization ---
;;
;; Motoi's evaluator supports proper tail calls. That means:
;;
;;   (define (loop n)
;;     (if (= n 0)
;;         'done
;;         (loop (- n 1))))
;;
;; This will run without growing the stack. `loop` is called in
;; tail position — the last thing `if` does. The evaluator recognizes
;; this and reuses the current stack frame.
;;
;; What this means for you: recursion is a first-class control-flow
;; primitive. You can write loops as tail-recursive functions and
;; the runtime will not grow the stack.
;;
;; --- Fuel budget ---
;;
;; Each evaluation has a fuel budget (default: 200,000 units). Each
;; step of evaluation consumes fuel. When fuel runs out, the runtime
;; halts with a fuel-exhausted error.
;;
;; What this means for you: the language protects itself against
;; runaway loops and pathological recursion. If you legitimately
;; need more fuel, pass `--fuel N` to the CLI. If you are hitting
;; the fuel limit accidentally, you have a bug.
;;
;; --- Closures capture environment ---
;;
;;   (define (make-adder n)
;;     (lambda (x) (+ x n)))
;;
;;   (define add5 (make-adder 5))
;;   (add5 3)  ; → 8
;;
;; The `lambda` inside `make-adder` closes over `n`. When `make-adder`
;; is called with 5, the returned lambda REMEMBERS n=5. Every closure
;; carries its own environment.
;;
;; This is the foundation of encapsulation in Motoi. You do not need
;; classes or objects — closures do the job. A closure is data that
;; behaves.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 8 — What all this means for you at the keyboard
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The practical consequence of everything above:
;;
;;   1. You can write a small program in ten lines that composes verbs
;;      from four libraries and it will work, because the libraries
;;      were designed to compose.
;;
;;   2. You can ask the runtime what any verb does at any time (see
;;      00b-introspection.slat), because the runtime knows.
;;
;;   3. You can read this reference manual as a MAP OF THE GRAPH.
;;      Each chapter is a region. Reading one chapter teaches you a
;;      region. Reading many chapters lets you compose across regions.
;;
;;   4. You do not need to memorize signatures — the REPL will tell
;;      you. You do not need to guess where a verb lives — `,apropos`
;;      will tell you. You do not need to fear macros — `,expand` will
;;      tell you.
;;
;; The language, the runtime, the reference, and the introspection
;; surface are all designed to work together. That is why this chapter
;; and 00b-introspection.slat are before the library catalog. You
;; read these first, and then everything else in this book makes
;; sense.
;;
;; And here is where we begin.
;;
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; End of chapter 00c.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
